[1] Japan (ex Mongolia)
Date: Wed 19 Aug 2015
From: Nakamura-Uchiyama F
<idfukyumi@naramed-u.ac.jp>


Imported measles from Mongolia to Japan
---------------------------------------
The World Health Organisation (WHO) certified that Mongolia was measles free in June 2014. Here we report a measles case of a Japanese patient who returned from Mongolia.

A 36-year-old Japanese man with a 6-day history of fever, cough, rhinorrhea, and rash was diagnosed with measles on 16 Jul 2015 after returning from Mongolia. He had been working as a Japanese-language teacher in Nalaiha, a suburb of Ulan Bator, for 5 years. He returned to Japan from Mongolia via Beijing on 7 Jul 2015 for a summer holiday. He did not visit any other countries or have any infectious diseases, and had no contact with sick people during his stay in Mongolia. The patient's vaccination records were unavailable. He had a mild case of measles in his childhood, according to his mother. A physical examination revealed generalised exanthema involving the palms and soles and small white papules (Koplik spots) on the bilateral buccal mucosa and gingiva. Laboratory results revealed thrombocytopenia with slight liver and kidney dysfunction. Upon admission to our hospital, supportive care was initiated. Serologic testing revealed anti-measles IgM and IgG titers of 9.21 and 10.6 on 16 Jul 2015 (acute phase) and 11.1 and 70.6 on 30 Jul 2015 (recovery phase), respectively. To confirm the diagnosis, his blood and pharyngeal swab samples was sent to the Nara Prefecture Institute of Health. The result revealed measles virus genotype H1, which is the same genotype detected in China and Mongolia. With his current medical history and laboratory data, we suspected that he was [infected with measles virus] in Mongolia.

An official report issued by the WHO Regional Office for the Western Pacific (WPRO)* confirmed a total of 750 measles cases in Mongolia between March and June 2015, although an International SOS** was issued to travelers regarding a measles outbreak in Mongolia at the end of May 2015 because of more than 8900 suspected cases, of which at least 100 were laboratory or clinically confirmed. There is a significant difference in the number of measles cases in 2 reports. It is uncertain whether measles outbreak is ongoing in Mongolia or not, but the risk of measles among travelers planning to visit Mongolia should be assessed to recommend adequate vaccination strategies.

[Addendum
See:
*http://iris.wpro.who.int/bitstream/10665.1/11373/1/Measles-Rubella_Bulletin_2015_Vol_09_No_07.pdf?ua=1
