[3] Australia (Queensland 1)
Date: Wed 19 Aug 2015
Source: Brisbane Times [summ., edited]
http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/fourth-measles-case-confirmed-at-uqs-st-lucia-campus-20150819-gj2utj.html


University of Queensland (Brisbane) confirms 4th case of measles since mid-July [2015]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The University of Queensland [UQ] has confirmed the 4th case of measles at its St Lucia campus since mid-July [2015]. Health officials said the latest student victim had attended a lecture with a previously confirmed measles sufferer. They said the student had visited a number of locations while infectious, including:

- University of Queensland, St Lucia, between Tuesday, 11 Aug 2015, and Wednesday, 19 Aug 2015
- Indooroopilly Shopping Centre, Thursday, 13 Aug 2015
- The Royal Exchange Hotel, Saturday, 15 Aug 2015
- Taringa Day and Night Medical Centre, evening of Sunday [Saturday?], 15 Aug 2015

Metro North Public Health physician James Smith said anyone at those locations who may have come into contact with the patient should speak to their GP if not certain about their own immunity.

"Measles is a very contagious virus that is spread from person to person by tiny droplets created during coughing and sneezing. The droplets can remain suspended in the air," Dr Smith said. "Measles can be distressing for those with the infection and can cause serious complications such as pneumonia and encephalitis (inflammation of the brain). We encourage people to check if they need to be vaccinated against measles."

The 1st person to suffer measles at UQ was a student who contracted the disease on an overseas holiday. They returned to Brisbane on 15 Jul 2015, and went to a number of public locations while infectious until being diagnosed 5 days later. Two other students have since been confirmed with the virus.

Dr Smith said the Metro North Public Health Unit would set up a vaccination clinic at the St Lucia campus this week, particularly targeting students living in residential colleges. He said the initial symptoms of measles include fever, lethargy, runny nose, moist cough and sore and red eyes. A blotchy red rash that often starts on the face follows a few days later, then spreads. "Symptoms usually start around 10 days after infection but sometimes longer. Anyone who develops measles-like symptoms should isolate themselves from school, work and social activities and seek medical advice," Dr Smith said.

"It's very important to call the medical practice first to say you could have measles, so that staff can take precautions to avoid spreading the disease to others."

