[4] Australia (Queensland 2)
Date: Wed 19 Aug 2015
Source: The Courier-Mail Newspaper, Brisbane [edited]
http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/university-of-queensland-measles-outbreak-fifth-student-tests-positive/story-fnihsrf2-1227491378825


A 5th University of Queensland student has tested positive to measles as an outbreak continues at the St Lucia campus in Brisbane's inner west
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Public health experts have set up a vaccination clinic at the campus, particularly targeting students at residential colleges.

A Queensland Health communicable diseases surveillance report shows the 1st case in the university outbreak contracted measles in Indonesia in July [2015] before returning to Brisbane.

One of the 5 students who have been diagnosed with the highly contagious virus in the past 5 weeks was infectious while attending lectures with the university's faculty of engineering. But the outbreak has not been confined to one faculty. The latest case takes the number of people diagnosed with measles in Queensland so far this year to 15, compared with 73 for the whole of 2014.

Metro North public health physician James Smith said people who had not been vaccinated against measles should speak to their general practitioner. "Measles can be distressing for those with the infection and can cause serious complications such as pneumonia and encephalitis (inflammation of the brain)," he said.

Initial symptoms include a fever, fatigue, runny nose, moist cough and sore and red eyes. This is followed a few days later by a blotchy red rash. The rash often starts on the face before spreading. "Symptoms usually start around 10 days after infection but sometimes longer," Dr Smith said. He said anyone who developed measles-like symptoms should isolate themselves from school, work and social activities and seek medical advice. "It's very important to call the medical practice first to say you could have measles, so that staff can take precautions to avoid spreading the disease to others," Dr Smith said.

